<p><br />
The following is a list of <a href="/wiki/Gods" class="mw-redirect" title="Gods">gods</a>, <a href="/wiki/Goddesses" class="mw-redirect" title="Goddesses">goddesses</a> and many other divine and semi-divine figures from ancient <a href="/wiki/Greek_mythology" title="Greek mythology">Greek mythology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_religion" title="Ancient Greek religion">ancient Greek religion</a>. The list does not include creatures; for these, see <a href="/wiki/List_of_Greek_mythological_creatures" title="List of Greek mythological creatures">List of Greek mythological creatures</a>.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Immortals">Immortals</span></h2>
<p>The Greeks created images of their deities for many purposes. A temple would house the statue of a god or goddess, or multiple deities, and might be decorated with <a href="/wiki/Relief" title="Relief">relief</a> scenes depicting myths. Divine images were common on coins. Drinking cups and other <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_pottery" class="mw-redirect" title="Ancient Greek pottery">vessels</a> were painted with scenes from Greek myths.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Major_gods_and_goddesses">Major gods and goddesses</span></h3>
<table class="wikitable" width="100%">

<tbody><tr>
<th>Deity
</th>
<th>Description
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg" class="image"><img alt="NAMA Aphrodite Syracuse.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg/160px-NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="409" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg/240px-NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg/320px-NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg 2x" data-file-width="674" data-file-height="1721" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Aphrodite" title="Aphrodite">Aphrodite</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Aphrodit</i>)
<p>Goddess of beauty, love, desire, and pleasure. In <a href="/wiki/Hesiod" title="Hesiod">Hesiod</a>'s <i>Theogony</i> (188206), she was born from sea-foam and the severed genitals of <a href="/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)" title="Uranus (mythology)">Uranus</a>; in <a href="/wiki/Homer" title="Homer">Homer</a>'s <i>Iliad</i> (5.370417), she is daughter of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dione_(Titaness)" title="Dione (Titaness)">Dione</a>. She was married to <a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a>, but bore him no children. She had many lovers, most notably <a href="/wiki/Ares" title="Ares">Ares</a>, to whom she bore <a href="/wiki/Harmonia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Harmonia (mythology)">Harmonia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(mythology)" title="Phobos (mythology)">Phobos</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Deimos (mythology)">Deimos</a>. She was also a lover to <a href="/wiki/Adonis" title="Adonis">Adonis</a> and <a href="/wiki/Anchises" title="Anchises">Anchises</a>, to whom she bore <a href="/wiki/Aeneas" title="Aeneas">Aeneas</a>. She is usually depicted as a naked or semi-nude beautiful woman. Her symbols include <a href="/wiki/Myrtus_communis" title="Myrtus communis">myrtle</a>, roses, and the <a href="/wiki/Scallop" title="Scallop">scallop</a> shell. Her sacred animals include doves and sparrows. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Venus_(mythology)" title="Venus (mythology)">Venus</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Pothos,_lira,_dan_angsa_(inv_6253_MANN).jpg" class="image"><img alt="Pothos, lira, dan angsa (inv 6253 MANN).jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg/160px-Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="257" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg/240px-Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg/320px-Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="374" data-file-height="600" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Apollo" title="Apollo">Apollo</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Aplln</i>)
<p>God of music, arts, knowledge, healing, plague, prophecy, poetry, manly beauty, and archery. He is the son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Leto" title="Leto">Leto</a>, and the twin brother of <a href="/wiki/Artemis" title="Artemis">Artemis</a>. Both Apollo and Artemis use a bow and arrow. Apollo is depicted as young, beardless, handsome and athletic. In myth, he can be cruel and destructive, and his love affairs are rarely happy. He is often accompanied by the Muses. His most famous temple is in <a href="/wiki/Delphi" title="Delphi">Delphi</a>, where he established his oracular shrine. His signs and symbols include the <a href="/wiki/Laurel_wreath" title="Laurel wreath">laurel wreath</a>, bow and arrow, and <a href="/wiki/Lyre" title="Lyre">lyre</a>. His sacred animals include <a href="/wiki/Roe_deer" title="Roe deer">roe deer</a>, swans, and pythons. Some late Roman and Greek poetry and mythography identifies him as a sun-god, equivalent to Roman <a href="/wiki/Sol_(Roman_mythology)" title="Sol (Roman mythology)">Sol</a> and Greek <a href="/wiki/Helios" title="Helios">Helios</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Ares Canope Villa Adriana b.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg/160px-Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="320" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg/240px-Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg/320px-Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg 2x" data-file-width="875" data-file-height="1750" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Ares" title="Ares">Ares</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>rs</i>)
<p>God of courage, war, bloodshed, and violence. The son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a>, he was depicted as a beardless youth, either nude with a helmet and spear or sword, or as an armed warrior. <a href="/wiki/Homer" title="Homer">Homer</a> portrays him as moody and unreliable, and as being the most unpopular god on earth and Olympus (<i>Iliad</i> 5.8901). He generally represents the chaos of war in contrast to <a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a>, a goddess of military strategy and skill. Ares is known for cuckolding his brother <a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a>, conducting an affair with his wife <a href="/wiki/Aphrodite" title="Aphrodite">Aphrodite</a>. His sacred animals include vultures, venomous snakes, dogs, and boars. His Roman counterpart <a href="/wiki/Mars_(mythology)" title="Mars (mythology)">Mars</a> by contrast was regarded as the dignified ancestor of the Roman people.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Diane de Versailles Leochares.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg/160px-Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="246" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg/240px-Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg/320px-Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="1230" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Artemis" title="Artemis">Artemis</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>rtemis</i>)
<p>Virgin goddess of the hunt, wilderness, animals, the Moon and young girls. In later times, Artemis became associated with bows and arrows. She is the daughter of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Leto" title="Leto">Leto</a>, and twin sister of <a href="/wiki/Apollo" title="Apollo">Apollo</a>. In art she is often depicted as a young woman dressed in a short knee-length <a href="/wiki/Chiton_(costume)" title="Chiton (costume)">chiton</a> and equipped with a hunting bow and a quiver of arrows. Her attributes include hunting spears, animal pelts, <a href="/wiki/Deer" title="Deer">deer</a> and other wild animals. Her sacred animal is a deer. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Diana_(mythology)" title="Diana (mythology)">Diana</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Mattei Athena Louvre Ma530 n2.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg/160px-Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="320" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg/240px-Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg/320px-Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1800" data-file-height="3600" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Athn</i>)
<p>Goddess of reason, wisdom, intelligence, skill, peace, warfare, battle strategy, and handicrafts. According to most traditions, she was born from Zeus's forehead, fully formed and armored. She is depicted as being crowned with a crested helm, armed with shield and spear, and wearing the <a href="/wiki/Aegis" title="Aegis">aegis</a> over a long dress. Poets describe her as "grey-eyed" or having especially bright, keen eyes. She is a special patron of <a href="/wiki/Greek_hero" class="mw-redirect" title="Greek hero">heroes</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Odysseus" title="Odysseus">Odysseus</a>. She is the patron of the city Athens (from which she takes her name) and is attributed to various inventions in arts and literature. Her symbol is the <a href="/wiki/Olive" title="Olive">olive</a> tree. She is commonly shown as being accompanied by her sacred animal, the owl. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Minerva" title="Minerva">Minerva</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Demeter Altemps Inv8546.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg/160px-Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="366" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg/240px-Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg/320px-Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1550" data-file-height="3550" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Demeter" title="Demeter">Demeter</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Dmtr</i>)
<p>Goddess of grain, agriculture, harvest, growth, and nourishment. Demeter, whose Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Ceres_(mythology)" title="Ceres (mythology)">Ceres</a>, is a daughter of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>, and was swallowed and then regurgitated by her father. She is a sister of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>, by whom she bore <a href="/wiki/Persephone" title="Persephone">Persephone</a>, who is also known as Kore, i.e. "the girl." One of the central myths associated with Demeter involves <a href="/wiki/Hades" title="Hades">Hades</a>' abduction of Persephone and Demeter's lengthy search for her. Demeter is one of the main deities of the <a href="/wiki/Eleusinian_Mysteries" title="Eleusinian Mysteries">Eleusinian Mysteries</a>, in which the rites seemed to center around Demeter's search for and reunion with her daughter, which symbolized both the rebirth of crops in spring and the rebirth of the initiates after death. She is depicted as a mature woman, often crowned and holding sheafs of <a href="/wiki/Wheat" title="Wheat">wheat</a> and a torch.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Her symbols are the <a href="/wiki/Cornucopia" title="Cornucopia">cornucopia</a>, wheat-ears, the winged serpent, and the lotus staff. Her sacred animals include pigs and snakes.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Dionysos Louvre Ma87 n2.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg/160px-Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="315" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg/240px-Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg/320px-Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1700" data-file-height="3350" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Dinusos</i>)/<b>Bacchus</b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Bkkhos</i>)
<p>God of wine, fruitfulness, parties, festivals, madness, chaos, drunkenness, vegetation, ecstasy, and the theater. He is the twice-born son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Semele" title="Semele">Semele</a>, in that Zeus snatched him from his mother's womb and stitched Dionysus into his own thigh and carried him until he was ready to be born. In art he is depicted as either an older bearded god (particularly before 430 BC) or an <a href="/wiki/Effeminacy" title="Effeminacy">effeminate</a>, long-haired youth (particularly after 430 BC). His attributes include the <a href="/wiki/Thyrsus" title="Thyrsus">thyrsus</a>, a drinking cup, the grape vine, and a crown of <a href="/wiki/Ivy" class="mw-redirect" title="Ivy">ivy</a>. He is often in the company of his <a href="/wiki/Thiasos" class="mw-redirect" title="Thiasos">thiasos</a>, a group of attendants including <a href="/wiki/Satyr" title="Satyr">satyrs</a>, <a href="/wiki/Maenad" title="Maenad">maenads</a>, and his old tutor <a href="/wiki/Silenus" title="Silenus">Silenus</a>. The consort of Dionysus was <a href="/wiki/Ariadne" title="Ariadne">Ariadne</a>. It was once held that Dionysius was a later addition to the Greek pantheon, but the discovery of <a href="/wiki/Linear_B" title="Linear B">Linear B</a> tablets confirm his status as a deity from an early period. Bacchus was another name for him in Greek, and came into common usage among the Romans.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> His sacred animals include dolphins, serpents, tigers, and donkeys.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg/160px-Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="296" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg/240px-Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg/320px-Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg 2x" data-file-width="489" data-file-height="904" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hades" title="Hades">Hades</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Hids</i>)/<b><a href="/wiki/Pluto_(mythology)" title="Pluto (mythology)">Pluto</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Ploutn</i>)
<p>King of the underworld and the dead. God of wealth. His consort is <a href="/wiki/Persephone" title="Persephone">Persephone</a>. His attributes are the <a href="/wiki/Drinking_horn" title="Drinking horn">drinking horn</a> or <a href="/wiki/Cornucopia" title="Cornucopia">cornucopia</a>, key, sceptre, and the three-headed dog <a href="/wiki/Cerberus" title="Cerberus">Cerberus</a>. His sacred animals include the screech owl. He was one of three sons of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>, and thus sovereign over one of the three realms of the universe, the underworld. As a <a href="/wiki/Chthonic" title="Chthonic">chthonic</a> god, however, his place among the Olympians is ambiguous. In the <a href="/wiki/Mystery_religions" class="mw-redirect" title="Mystery religions">mystery religions</a> and Athenian literature, Plouton ("the Rich one") was his preferred name, because of the idea that all riches came from the earth. The term <i>Hades</i> was used in this literature to refer to the underworld itself. The Romans translated <i>Plouton</i> as <a href="/wiki/Dis_Pater" class="mw-redirect" title="Dis Pater">Dis Pater</a> ("the Rich Father") or Pluto.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Vulcan Coustou Louvre MR1814.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg/160px-Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="241" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg/240px-Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg/320px-Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2000" data-file-height="3008" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Hphaistos</i>)
<p>God of fire, metalworking, and crafts. Either the son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a> or Hera alone, he is the smith of the gods and the husband of the adulterous <a href="/wiki/Aphrodite" title="Aphrodite">Aphrodite</a>. He was usually depicted as a bearded, crippled man with hammer, tongs, and anvil, and sometimes riding a donkey. His sacred animals include the donkey, the guard dog, and the crane. Among his creations was the armor of <a href="/wiki/Achilles" title="Achilles">Achilles</a>. Hephaestus used the fire of the forge as a creative force, but his Roman counterpart <a href="/wiki/Vulcan_(mythology)" title="Vulcan (mythology)">Vulcan</a> was feared for his destructive potential and associated with the <a href="/wiki/Volcanism" title="Volcanism">volcanic power</a> of the earth.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hera Campana Louvre Ma2283.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg/160px-Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="292" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg/240px-Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg/320px-Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1947" data-file-height="3551" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Hra</i>)
<p>Queen of the gods, and goddess of marriage, women, childbirth, heirs, kings, and empires. She is the wife and sister of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>, and the daughter of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>. She was usually depicted as a regal woman in the prime of her life, wearing a diadem and veil and holding a lotus-tipped staff. Although she is the goddess of marriage, Zeus's many infidelities drive her to jealousy and vengefulness. Her sacred animals include the heifer, the peacock, and the cuckoo. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Juno_(mythology)" title="Juno (mythology)">Juno</a>.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hermes Ingenui Pio-Clementino Inv544.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg/160px-Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="350" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg/240px-Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg/320px-Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="3500" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hermes" title="Hermes">Hermes</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Hrms</i>)
<p>God of boundaries, travel, communication, trade, language, thieves and writing. Hermes was also responsible for protecting livestock and presided over the spheres associated with fertility, music, luck, and deception.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> The son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Maia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Maia (mythology)">Maia</a>, Hermes is the messenger of the gods, and a <a href="/wiki/Psychopomp" title="Psychopomp">psychopomp</a> who leads the souls of the dead into the afterlife. He was depicted either as a handsome and athletic beardless youth, or as an older bearded man. His attributes include the herald's wand or <a href="/wiki/Caduceus" title="Caduceus">caduceus</a>, winged sandals, and a traveler's cap. His sacred animals include the tortoise. His Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Mercury_(mythology)" title="Mercury (mythology)">Mercury</a>.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hestia Giustiniani.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg/160px-Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="300" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg/240px-Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg/320px-Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg 2x" data-file-width="483" data-file-height="907" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hestia" title="Hestia">Hestia</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Hesta</i>)
<p>Virgin goddess of the hearth, home, and chastity. She is a daughter of <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a>, and a sister of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>. Not often identifiable in Greek art, she appeared as a modestly veiled woman. Her symbols are the hearth and kettle. In some accounts, she gave up her seat as one of the <a href="/wiki/Twelve_Olympians" title="Twelve Olympians">Twelve Olympians</a> in favor of <a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a>, and she plays little role in Greek myths. Her Roman counterpart <a href="/wiki/Vesta_(mythology)" title="Vesta (mythology)">Vesta</a>, however, was a major deity of the Roman state.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg" class="image"><img alt="0036MAN Poseidon.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg/160px-0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="213" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg/240px-0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg/320px-0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg 2x" data-file-width="743" data-file-height="990" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Poseidon" title="Poseidon">Poseidon</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Poseidn</i>)
<p>God of the sea, rivers, floods, droughts, and earthquakes. He is a son of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>, and the brother of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hades" title="Hades">Hades</a>. He rules one of the three realms of the universe, as king of the sea and the waters. In art he is depicted as a mature man of sturdy build, often with a luxuriant beard, and holding a <a href="/wiki/Trident" title="Trident">trident</a>. His sacred animals include the horse and the dolphin. His wedding with <a href="/wiki/Amphitrite" title="Amphitrite">Amphitrite</a> is often presented as a <a href="/wiki/Thiasos#Other_thiasoi" class="mw-redirect" title="Thiasos">triumphal procession</a>. In some stories he rapes Medusa, leading to her transformation into a hideous Gorgon and also to the birth of their two children, Pegasus and Chrysaor. His Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)" title="Neptune (mythology)">Neptune</a>.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Jupiter Smyrna Louvre Ma13.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg/160px-Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="333" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg/240px-Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg/320px-Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1800" data-file-height="3750" /></a>
</td>
<td><b> <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>, <i>Zes</i>)
<p>King of the gods, ruler of Mount Olympus, and god of the sky, weather, thunder, lightning, law, order, and justice. He is the youngest son of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>. He overthrew Cronus and gained the sovereignty of heaven for himself. In art he is depicted as a regal, mature man with a sturdy figure and dark beard. His usual attributes are the royal scepter and the lightning bolt. His sacred animals include the eagle and the bull. His Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)" title="Jupiter (mythology)">Jupiter</a>, also known as Jove.
</p>
</td></tr></tbody></table>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Titans_and_Titanesses"><a href="/wiki/Titan_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Titan (mythology)">Titans and Titanesses</a></span></h3>

<td><a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a></td>
<td>Titan of harvests and personification of destructive time. The leader of the Titans, who overthrew his father <a href="/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)" title="Uranus (mythology)">Uranus</a> only to be overthrown in turn by his son, <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>. Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/Chronos" title="Chronos">Chronos</a>.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span> (<i>Hypern</i>)</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Hyperion_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Hyperion (mythology)">Hyperion</a></td>
<td>Titan of light. With <a href="/wiki/Theia" title="Theia">Theia</a>, he is the father of <a href="/wiki/Helios" title="Helios">Helios</a> (the sun), <a href="/wiki/Selene" title="Selene">Selene</a> (the moon), and <a href="/wiki/Eos" title="Eos">Eos</a> (the dawn).
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span> (<i>Iapets</i>)</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Iapetus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Iapetus (mythology)">Iapetus</a></td>
<td>Titan of mortality and father of <a href="/wiki/Prometheus" title="Prometheus">Prometheus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Epimetheus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Epimetheus (mythology)">Epimetheus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Menoetius_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Menoetius (mythology)">Menoetius</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Atlas_(mythology)" title="Atlas (mythology)">Atlas</a>.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">M</span> (<i>Mnmosn</i>)</td>

<h3><span id="Gigantes_and_other_.22giants.22"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Gigantes_and_other_&quot;giants&quot;">Gigantes and other "giants"</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width:&#32;; -webkit-column-width:&#32;; column-width:&#32;;">
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Gigantes">Gigantes</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg/220px-Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="215" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg/330px-Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg/440px-Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2250" data-file-height="2200" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a> (left) fighting Enceladus (inscribed retrograde) on an <a href="/wiki/Attica" title="Attica">Attic</a> <a href="/wiki/Red-figure_pottery" title="Red-figure pottery">red-figure</a> dish, c. 550500&#160;BC (<a href="/wiki/Louvre" title="Louvre">Louvre</a> CA3662).<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Gigantes" class="mw-redirect" title="Gigantes">Gigantes</a> were the offspring of <a href="/wiki/Gaia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaia (mythology)">Gaia</a> (Earth), born from the blood that fell when <a href="/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)" title="Uranus (mythology)">Uranus</a> (Sky) was castrated by their <a href="/wiki/Titan_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Titan (mythology)">Titan</a> son <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a>, who fought the Gigantomachy, their war with the <a href="/wiki/Olympian_gods" class="mw-redirect" title="Olympian gods">Olympian gods</a> for supremacy of the cosmos, they include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Alcyoneus" title="Alcyoneus">Alcyoneus</a> (), a giant usually considered to be one of the Gigantes, slain by Heracles.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chthonius" title="Chthonius">Chthonius</a> ().</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Damysus_(Giant)" title="Damysus (Giant)">Damysus</a> (), the fastest of all the Giants in the Greek mythology.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Enceladus_(Giant)" class="mw-redirect" title="Enceladus (Giant)">Enceladus</a> (), typically slain by <a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a>, said to be buried under <a href="/wiki/Mount_Etna" title="Mount Etna">Mount Etna</a> in <a href="/wiki/Sicily" title="Sicily">Sicily</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mimas_(Giant)" title="Mimas (Giant)">Mimas</a> (), according to <a href="/wiki/Bibliotheca_(Pseudo-Apollodorus)" title="Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)">Apollodorus</a>, he was killed by <a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a>, or by others <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> or <a href="/wiki/Ares" title="Ares">Ares</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pallas_(Giant)" title="Pallas (Giant)">Pallas</a> (), according to <a href="/wiki/Bibliotheca_(Pseudo-Apollodorus)" title="Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)">Apollodorus</a>, he was flayed by Athena, who used his skin as a shield.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Polybotes" title="Polybotes">Polybotes</a> (), typically slain by <a href="/wiki/Poseidon" title="Poseidon">Poseidon</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Porphyrion" title="Porphyrion">Porphyrion</a> (), one of the leaders of the Gigantes, typically slain by <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Giants_(Greek_mythology)#Named_Giants" title="Giants (Greek mythology)">Thoas/Thoon</a> (), he was killed by the <a href="/wiki/Moirai" title="Moirai">Moirai</a>.
<ul><li><i>For a more complete list of Gigantes see <a href="/wiki/Giants_(Greek_mythology)#Named_Giants" title="Giants (Greek mythology)">Giants (Greek mythology)#Named Giants</a>.</i></li></ul></li></ul>
<h4><span id="Other_.22giants.22"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_&quot;giants&quot;">Other "giants"</span></h4>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aloadae" title="Aloadae">Aloadae</a> (), twin giants who attempted to climb to Olympus by piling mountains on top of each other.
<ul><li>Otus or Otos ()</li>
<li>Ephialtes ()</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anax" title="Anax">Anax</a> () was a giant of the island of Lade near Miletos in Lydia, Anatolia.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antaeus" title="Antaeus">Antaeus</a> (), a Libyan giant who wrestled all visitors to the death until he was slain by Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antiphates" title="Antiphates">Antiphates</a> (), the king of the man-eating giants known as Laestrygones which were encountered by Odysseus on his travels.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Argus_Panoptes" title="Argus Panoptes">Argus Panoptes</a> ( ), a hundred-eyed giant tasked with guarding over Io</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asterius_(Giant)" class="mw-redirect" title="Asterius (Giant)">Asterius</a> (), a Lydian giant.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cacus" title="Cacus">Cacus</a> (), a fire-breathing Latin giant slain by Heracles.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cyclopes" title="Cyclopes">Cyclopes</a> (Hesiodic), three one-eyed giants who forged the lightning-bolts of Zeus, Trident of Poseidon and Helmet of Hades
<ul><li>Arges ()</li>
<li>Brontes ()</li>
<li>Steropes ()</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cyclopes" title="Cyclopes">Cyclopes</a> (Homeric), a tribe of one-eyed, man-eating giants who herded flocks of sheep on the island of Sicily
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Polyphemus" title="Polyphemus">Polyphemus</a> (), a Cyclops who briefly captured <a href="/wiki/Odysseus" title="Odysseus">Odysseus</a> and his men, only to be overcome and blinded by the hero</li></ul></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Gegenees" title="Gegenees">Gegenees</a> (), a tribe of six-armed giants fought by the Argonauts on Bear Mountain in Mysia</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Geryon" title="Geryon">Geryon</a> (), a three-bodied giant who dwelt on the sunset isle at the ends of the earth. He was slain by Heracles when the hero arrived to fetch the giant's cattle as one of his twelve labours.</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Hekatoncheires" class="mw-redirect" title="Hekatoncheires">Hekatoncheires</a> (), or Centimanes (Latin), the Hundred-Handed Ones, giant gods of violent storms and hurricanes. Three sons of Uranus and Gaia, each with his own distinct characters.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
<ul><li>Briareus () or Aigaion (), The Vigorous</li>
<li>Cottus (), The Furious</li>
<li>Gyges (), The Big-Limbed</li></ul></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Laestrygonians" title="Laestrygonians">Laestrygonians</a> (), a tribe of man-eating giants encountered by Odysseus on his travels</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orion_(mythology)" title="Orion (mythology)">Orion</a> (), a giant huntsman whom Zeus placed among the stars as the <a href="/wiki/Orion_(constellation)" title="Orion (constellation)">constellation of Orion</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Talos" title="Talos">Talos</a> (), a giant forged from bronze by Hephaestus, and given by Zeus to his lover Europa as her personal protector</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tityos" title="Tityos">Tityos</a> (), a giant slain by Apollo and Artemis when he attempted to violate their mother Leto.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Typhon" title="Typhon">Typhon</a> (), a monstrous immortal storm-giant who attempted to launch an attack on <a href="/wiki/Mount_Olympus" title="Mount Olympus">Mount Olympus</a> but was defeated by the Olympians and imprisoned in the pits of Tartarus</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Personified_concepts">Personified concepts</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Achlys" title="Achlys">Achlys</a> (), spirit of the death-mist, personification of sadness, misery and poison</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Adephagia" title="Adephagia">Adephagia</a> (), spirit of satiety and gluttony</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Adikia" title="Adikia">Adikia</a> (), spirit of injustice and wrongdoing</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aergia" title="Aergia">Aergia</a> (), spirit of idleness, laziness, indolence and sloth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Agathodaemon" title="Agathodaemon">Agathodaemon</a> (), spirit of the <a href="/wiki/Vineyard" title="Vineyard">vineyards</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cereal" title="Cereal">grainfields</a>. Ensuring good <a href="/wiki/Luck" title="Luck">luck</a>, <a href="/wiki/Health" title="Health">health</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Wisdom" title="Wisdom">wisdom</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Agon" title="Agon">Agon</a> (), spirit of contest, who possessed an altar at Olympia, site of the Olympic Games.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aidos" title="Aidos">Aidos</a> (), spirit of modesty, reverence and respect</li>
<li>Aisa (), personification of lot and fate</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alala" title="Alala">Alala</a> (), spirit of the war cry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alastor" title="Alastor">Alastor</a> (), spirit of blood feuds and vengeance</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aletheia" title="Aletheia">Aletheia</a> (), spirit of truth, truthfulness and sincerity</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Algos" title="Algos">Algea</a> (), spirits of pain and suffering
<ul><li>Achos () "trouble, distress"</li>
<li>Ania () "ache, anguish"</li>
<li>Lupe () "pain, grief, sadness"</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alke" title="Alke">Alke</a> (), spirit of prowess and courage (one of the <a href="/wiki/Machai" title="Machai">Machai</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amechania" title="Amechania">Amechania</a> (), spirit of helplessness and want of means</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Amphilogiai" class="mw-redirect" title="Amphilogiai">Amphilogiai</a> (), spirits of disputes, debate, and contention</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anaideia" title="Anaideia">Anaideia</a> (), spirit of ruthlessness, shamelessness, and unforgivingness</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Androktasiai" title="Androktasiai">Androktasiai</a> (), spirits of battlefield slaughter</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Angelia" title="Angelia">Angelia</a> (), spirit of messages, tidings and proclamations</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Apate_(deity)" class="mw-redirect" title="Apate (deity)">Apate</a> (), spirit of deceit, guile, fraud and deception</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Apheleia" title="Apheleia">Apheleia</a> (), spirit of simplicity</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Arae" title="Arae">Arae</a> (), spirits of curses</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arete_(moral_virtue)#Personification" class="mw-redirect" title="Arete (moral virtue)">Arete</a> (), spirit of virtue, excellence, goodness, and valour</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/At%C3%AB" title="At">At</a> (), spirit of delusion, infatuation, blind folly, recklessness, and ruin</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bia_(mythology)" title="Bia (mythology)">Bia</a> ( "Violence"), the personification of force and raw energy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Caerus" title="Caerus">Caerus</a> (), spirit of opportunity</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Corus_(mythology)" title="Corus (mythology)">Corus</a> (), spirit of surfeit</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Deimos_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Deimos (mythology)">Deimos</a> (), spirit of fear, dread, and terror</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dikaiosyne" class="mw-redirect" title="Dikaiosyne">Dikaiosyne</a> (), spirit of justice and righteousness</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dike_(mythology)" title="Dike (mythology)">Dike</a> (), spirit of justice, fair judgement, and the rights established by custom and law</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dolos_(mythology)" title="Dolos (mythology)">Dolos</a> (), spirit of trickery, cunning deception, craftiness, treachery, and guile</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dysnomia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Dysnomia (mythology)">Dysnomia</a> (), spirit of lawlessness and poor civil constitution</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dyssebeia" title="Dyssebeia">Dyssebeia</a> (), spirit of impiety</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eirene_(Greek_goddess)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eirene (Greek goddess)">Eirene</a> (), goddess of peace</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eiresione" title="Eiresione">Eiresione</a> (), personification of the olive branch</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ekecheiria" title="Ekecheiria">Ekecheiria</a> (), spirit of truce, armistice, and the cessation of all hostilities; honoured at the Olympic Games</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eleos" title="Eleos">Eleos</a> (), spirit of mercy, pity, and compassion</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Elpis" title="Elpis">Elpis</a> (), spirit of hope and expectation</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Epiphron" title="Epiphron">Epiphron</a> (), spirit of prudence, shrewdness, thoughtfulness, carefulness, and sagacity</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eris_(mythology)" title="Eris (mythology)">Eris</a> (), spirit of strife, discord, contention, and rivalry</li></ul>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg/170px-Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="340" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg/255px-Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg/340px-Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2083" data-file-height="4166" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Eros_type_Centocelle_MAN_Napoli_Inv6353_n01.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Eros</div></div></div>
<ul><li>The <a href="/wiki/Erotes_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Erotes (mythology)">Erotes</a> ()
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Anteros" title="Anteros">Anteros</a> (), god of requited love</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eros_(god)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eros (god)">Eros</a> (), god of love and sexual intercourse</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hedylogos" title="Hedylogos">Hedylogos</a> (), god of sweet talk and flattery</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hermaphroditus" title="Hermaphroditus">Hermaphroditus</a> (), god of unions, androgyny, marriage, sexuality and fertility</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Himeros" class="mw-redirect" title="Himeros">Himeros</a> (), god of sexual desire</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hymen_(god)" title="Hymen (god)">Hymen</a> () or Hymenaeus (), god of marriage ceremonies, inspiring feasts and song</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pothos_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pothos (mythology)">Pothos</a> (), god of sexual longing, yearning, and desire</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eucleia" title="Eucleia">Eucleia</a> (), spirit of good repute and glory</li>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Chthonic_deities"><a href="/wiki/Chthonic" title="Chthonic">Chthonic</a> deities</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Amphiaraus" title="Amphiaraus">Amphiaraus</a> (), a seer, and one of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_against_Thebes" title="Seven against Thebes">Seven against Thebes</a> who became an oracular spirit of the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Angelos_(Greek_mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Angelos (Greek mythology)">Angelos</a> (), a daughter of Zeus and Hera who became an underworld goddess</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ascalaphus" title="Ascalaphus">Askalaphos</a> (), the son of Acheron and Orphne who tended the Underworld orchards before being transformed into a screech owl by Demeter</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Charon_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Charon (mythology)">Charon</a> (), ferryman of Hades</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> (), deposed king of the Titans; after his release from Tartarus he was appointed king of the Island of the Blessed</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Erebus" title="Erebus">Erebos</a> (), the primeval god of darkness, his mists encircled the underworld and filled the hollows of the earth</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Erinyes" title="Erinyes">Erinyes</a> (), the Furies, goddesses of retribution, known as "The Kindly Ones"
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Alecto" title="Alecto">Alecto</a> (), the unceasing one</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tisiphone" title="Tisiphone">Tisiphone</a> (), avenger of murder</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Megaera" title="Megaera">Megaera</a> (), the jealous one</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hecate" title="Hecate">Hecate</a> (), goddess of magic, witchcraft, the night, moon, ghosts, and necromancy</li>
<li>Judges of the Dead
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aeacus" title="Aeacus">Aiakos</a> (), former mortal king of Aegina, guardian of the keys of Hades and judge of the men of Europe</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Minos" title="Minos">Minos</a> (), former mortal king of Crete and judge of the final vote</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Rhadamanthus" title="Rhadamanthus">Rhadamanthys</a> (), former mortal lawmaker and judge of the men of Asia</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Keuthonymos" class="mw-redirect" title="Keuthonymos">Keuthonymos</a> (), an Underworld spirit and father of Menoetes</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lampads" class="mw-redirect" title="Lampads">Lampades</a> (), torch-bearing Underworld nymphs
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Gorgyra" class="mw-redirect" title="Gorgyra">Gorgyra</a> ()</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orphne" title="Orphne">Orphne</a> (), a Lampad nymph of Hades, mother of Askalaphos</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Macaria" title="Macaria">Macaria</a> (), daughter of Hades and goddess of blessed death (not to be confused with the daughter of <a href="/wiki/Heracles" title="Heracles">Heracles</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Melinoe" class="mw-redirect" title="Melinoe">Melinoe</a> (), daughter of Persephone and Zeus who presided over the propitiations offered to the ghosts of the dead</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Menoetius_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Menoetius (mythology)">Menoetes</a> (), an Underworld spirit who herded the cattle of Hades</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nyx_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Nyx (mythology)">Nyx</a> (), the primeval goddess of night</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hades_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Hades (mythology)">Hades</a> () God of underworld and all things beneath the earth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Persephone" title="Persephone">Persephone</a> (), queen of the underworld, wife of Hades and goddess of spring growth</li>
<li>Rivers of the Underworld
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Acheron" title="Acheron">Acheron</a> (), the river of woe</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alpheus_(deity)" title="Alpheus (deity)">Alpheus</a> (), the white river</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cocytus" title="Cocytus">Kokytos</a> (K), the river of wailing</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eridanos_(river_of_Hades)" title="Eridanos (river of Hades)">Eridanos</a> (), the river of amber</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lethe" title="Lethe">Lethe</a> (), the river of forgetfulness (its counterpart was the waters of <a href="/wiki/Mnemosyne" title="Mnemosyne">Mnemosyne</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phlegethon" title="Phlegethon">Phlegethon</a> (), the river of fire</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Styx" title="Styx">Styx</a> (), the river of hatred and oaths</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tartarus" title="Tartarus">Tartarus</a> (), the primeval god of the dark, stormy pit of Hades</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thanatos" title="Thanatos">Thanatos</a> (), god of death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Zagreus" title="Zagreus">Zagreus</a> (), an underworld god, possibly a son of Zeus and Persephone</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sea_deities"><a href="/wiki/Greek_sea_gods" title="Greek sea gods">Sea deities</a></span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 35em; -webkit-column-width: 35em; column-width: 35em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Hecatonchires" class="mw-redirect" title="Hecatonchires">Aegaeon</a> (), god of violent sea storms and ally of the Titans</li>

<li><a href="/wiki/Benthesikyme" title="Benthesikyme">Benthesikyme</a> (), daughter of Poseidon, who resided in <a href="/wiki/Ethiopia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ethiopia (mythology)">Ethiopia</a></li>

<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Arethusa_(mythology)" title="Arethusa (mythology)">Arethusa</a> (), a daughter of <a href="/wiki/Nereus" title="Nereus">Nereus</a> who was transformed into a fountain</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dynamene" title="Dynamene">Dynamene</a> (), associated with the might and power of great ocean swells</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Galene_(mythology)" title="Galene (mythology)">Galene</a> (), goddess of calm seas</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Psamathe_(Nereid)" title="Psamathe (Nereid)">Psamathe</a> (), goddess of sand beaches</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thetis" title="Thetis">Thetis</a> (), leader of the Nereids who presided over the spawning of marine life in the sea</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nereus" title="Nereus">Nereus</a> (), the old man of the sea, and the god of the sea's rich bounty of fish</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nerites_(mythology)" title="Nerites (mythology)">Nerites</a> (), a sea spirit who was transformed into a shell-fish by Aphrodite</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Oceanid" class="mw-redirect" title="Oceanid">Oceanides</a> (), sea nymphs, and patronesses of bodies of fresh water
<dl><dd><i>Some notable Oceanides include:</i></dd></dl>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Idyia" title="Idyia">Idyia</a> (), wife of the Colchian king <a href="/wiki/Aeetes" class="mw-redirect" title="Aeetes">Aeetes</a>, mother of <a href="/wiki/Medea" title="Medea">Medea</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Metis_(mythology)" title="Metis (mythology)">Metis</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>' first wife, whom Zeus impregnated with <a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a> and then swallowed.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Styx" title="Styx">Styx</a>, goddess of the river Styx</li></ul>
<dl><dd><i>For a more complete list, see <a href="/wiki/List_of_Oceanids" title="List of Oceanids">List of Oceanids</a></i></dd></dl></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Oceanus" title="Oceanus">Oceanus</a> (), Titan god of the Earth-encircling river Oceanus (the ocean), the fountain of all the Earth's fresh water</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Potamoi" title="Potamoi">Potamoi</a> (), Gods of rivers and streams of the earth
<dl><dd><i>Some notable river gods include:</i></dd></dl>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Achelous" title="Achelous">Achelous</a>, the god of the <a href="/wiki/Achelous_River" title="Achelous River">Achelous River</a>, the largest river in Greece, who gave his daughter in marriage to <a href="/wiki/Alcmaeon_(mythology)" title="Alcmaeon (mythology)">Alcmaeon</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alpheus_(deity)" title="Alpheus (deity)">Alpheus</a>, who fell in love with the <a href="/wiki/Nymph" title="Nymph">nymph</a> <a href="/wiki/Arethusa_(mythology)" title="Arethusa (mythology)">Arethusa</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Inachus" title="Inachus">Inachus</a>, the first king of Argos and progenitor of Argive line through his son grandson Argus.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nilus_(mythology)" title="Nilus (mythology)">Nilus</a>, Egyptian river god and the father of numerous daughters that mingled with the descendants of Inachus.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Peneus" title="Peneus">Peneus</a>, river god of Thessaly flowing from the foot of Pindus. He was the father of <a href="/wiki/Daphne" title="Daphne">Daphne</a> and <a href="/wiki/Stilbe" title="Stilbe">Stilbe</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Scamander" title="Scamander">Scamander</a>, who fought on the side of the <a href="/wiki/Troy" title="Troy">Trojans</a> during the <a href="/wiki/Trojan_War" title="Trojan War">Trojan War</a>.</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Palaemon_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Palaemon (mythology)">Palaemon</a> (), a young sea god who aided sailors in distress</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phorcys" title="Phorcys">Phorcys</a> (), god of the hidden dangers of the deep</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pontus_(mythology)" title="Pontus (mythology)">Pontos</a> (), primeval god of the sea, father of the fish and other sea creatures</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Proteus" title="Proteus">Proteus</a> (), a shape-shifting, prophetic old sea god, and the herdsman of Poseidon's seals</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Poseidon" title="Poseidon">Poseidon</a> (), king of the sea and lord of the sea gods; also god of rivers, flood and drought, earthquakes, and horses</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sangarius_(mythology)" title="Sangarius (mythology)">Sangarius</a> (), a river-god</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Telchines" title="Telchines">Telchines</a> (), sea spirits native to the island of Rhodes; the gods killed them when they turned to evil magic

<li><a href="/wiki/Tethys_(mythology)" title="Tethys (mythology)">Tethys</a> (), Titan goddess of the sources of fresh water, and the mother of the rivers, springs, streams, fountains, and clouds</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thalassa_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Thalassa (mythology)">Thalassa</a> (), primeval goddess of the sea and consort of Pontos</li>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sky_deities">Sky deities</span></h3>

<li>Omodamos (), crudebake</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Deipneus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Deipneus (mythology)">Deipneus</a> (), demi-god of the preparation of meals, specifically the making of bread</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eileithyia" title="Eileithyia">Eileithyia</a> (), goddess of childbirth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Enyalius" title="Enyalius">Enyalius</a> (), minor god of war</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Enyo" title="Enyo">Enyo</a> (), goddess of destructive war</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Epidotes" title="Epidotes">Epidotes</a> (), a divinity who was worshipped at <a href="/wiki/Lacedaemon" class="mw-redirect" title="Lacedaemon">Lacedaemon</a><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Glycon" title="Glycon">Glycon</a> (), a snake god</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Harpocrates" title="Harpocrates">Harpocrates</a> (), god of silence</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hebe_(mythology)" title="Hebe (mythology)">Hebe</a> (), goddess of youth and cup-bearer to the Olympians</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hermaphroditus" title="Hermaphroditus">Hermaphroditus</a> (), god of <a href="/wiki/Hermaphrodites" class="mw-redirect" title="Hermaphrodites">hermaphrodites</a> and effeminate men</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Horae" title="Horae">Horae</a> (), The Hours, the goddesses of natural order
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Eunomia_(goddess)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eunomia (goddess)">Eunomia</a> (), spirit of good order, and springtime goddess of green pastures</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dike_(mythology)" title="Dike (mythology)">Dike</a> (), spirit of justice, may have represented springtime growth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eirene_(Greek_goddess)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eirene (Greek goddess)">Eirene</a> (), spirit of peace and goddess of the springtime</li>
<li>The goddesses of springtime growth
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Thallo" class="mw-redirect" title="Thallo">Thallo</a> (), goddess of spring buds and shoots, identified with Eirene</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Auxo" class="mw-redirect" title="Auxo">Auxo</a> (), goddess of spring growth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Horae" title="Horae">Karpo</a> (), goddess of the fruits of the earth</li></ul></li>
<li>The goddesses of welfare
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Pherousa" class="mw-redirect" title="Pherousa">Pherousa</a> () "the bringer"</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Euporie" class="mw-redirect" title="Euporie">Euporie</a> () "abundance"</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Horae" title="Horae">Orthosie</a> () "prosperity"</li></ul></li>
<li>The goddesses of the natural portions of time and the times of day
<ul><li>Auge (), first light of the morning</li>
<li>Anatole () or Anatolia (), sunrise</li>
<li>Mousika or Musica (), the morning hour of music and study</li>
<li>Gymnastika, Gymnastica () or Gymnasia (), the morning hour of gymnastics/exercise</li>
<li>Nymphe (), the morning hour of ablutions (bathing, washing)</li>
<li>Mesembria (), noon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sponde" title="Sponde">Sponde</a> (), libations poured after lunch</li>
<li>Elete, prayer, the first of the afternoon work hours</li>
<li>Akte, Acte () or Cypris (), eating and pleasure, the second of the afternoon work hours</li>
<li>Hesperis (), evening</li>
<li>Dysis (), sunset</li>
<li>Arktos (), night sky, constellation</li></ul></li>
<li>The goddesses of seasons of the year
<ul><li>Eiar (), spring</li>
<li>Theros (), summer</li>
<li>Pthinoporon (), autumn</li>
<li>Cheimon (), winter</li></ul></li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hymenaios" class="mw-redirect" title="Hymenaios">Hymenaios</a> (), god of marriage and marriage feasts</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ichnaea" title="Ichnaea">Ichnaea</a> (), goddess of tracking</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iynx" title="Iynx">Iynx</a> (), goddess of the love charm</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Matton_(mythology)" title="Matton (mythology)">Matton</a> (), demi-god of the meal, specifically the kneading of dough</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mene_(goddess)" title="Mene (goddess)">Mene</a>, goddess of the months</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Muse" class="mw-redirect" title="Muse">Muses</a> (), goddesses of music, song and dance, and the source of inspiration to poets
<ul><li>Titan Muses, daughters of <a href="/wiki/Uranus" title="Uranus">Uranus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gaia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaia (mythology)">Gaia</a>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aoide" class="mw-redirect" title="Aoide">Aoide</a> (), muse of song</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arche_(mythology)" title="Arche (mythology)">Arche</a> (), muse of origins</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Melete" title="Melete">Melete</a> (), muse of meditation and practice</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mneme" title="Mneme">Mneme</a> (), muse of memory</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thelxinoe" class="mw-redirect" title="Thelxinoe">Thelxinoe</a> (), muse "charmer of minds"</li></ul></li>
<li>Olympian Muses, daughters of Zeus and Mnemosyne
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Calliope" title="Calliope">Calliope</a> (), muse of epic poetry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Clio" title="Clio">Clio</a> (), muse of history</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Euterpe" title="Euterpe">Euterpe</a> (), muse of musical poetry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Erato" title="Erato">Erato</a> (), muse of lyric poetry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Melpomene" title="Melpomene">Melpomene</a> (), muse of tragedy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Polyhymnia" title="Polyhymnia">Polyhymnia</a> () or (), muse of sacred poetry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Terpsichore" title="Terpsichore">Terpsichore</a> (), muse of dance and choral poetry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thalia_(Muse)" title="Thalia (Muse)">Thalia</a> (), muse of comedy and bucolic poetry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Urania" title="Urania">Urania</a> (), muse of astronomy</li></ul></li>
<li>Muses worshiped at <a href="/wiki/Delphi" title="Delphi">Delphi</a>, daughters of Apollo
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Cephisso" title="Cephisso">Cephisso</a> ()</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Apollonis" title="Apollonis">Apollonis</a> ()</li>

<li>Muses worshiped at <a href="/wiki/Sicyon" title="Sicyon">Sicyon</a>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Polymatheia" title="Polymatheia">Polymatheia</a> (), muse of knowledge</li></ul></li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Palaestra_(mythology)#Palaestra,_daughter_of_Hermes" title="Palaestra (mythology)">Palaestra</a> (), goddess of wrestling</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Rhapso" title="Rhapso">Rhapso</a> (), minor goddess or nymph whose name apparently refers to sewing</li></ul>
</div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Mortals">Mortals</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Deified_mortals">Deified mortals</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Achilles" title="Achilles">Achilles</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), hero of the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeacus" title="Aeacus">Aiakos</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a king of Aegina, appointed as a Judge of the Dead in the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeolus" title="Aeolus">Aeolus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a king of Thessaly, made the immortal king of all the winds by Zeus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alabandus" title="Alabandus">Alabandus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), he was the founder of the town of <a href="/wiki/Alabanda" title="Alabanda">Alabanda</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphiaraus" title="Amphiaraus">Amphiaraus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a hero of the war of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_against_Thebes" title="Seven against Thebes">Seven against Thebes</a> who became an oracular spirit of the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ariadne" title="Ariadne">Ariadne</a> (), a Cretan princess who became the immortal wife of Dionysus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aristaeus" title="Aristaeus">Aristaeus</a> (), a Thessalian hero, his inventions saw him immortalised as the god of bee-keeping, cheese-making, herding, olive-growing, and hunting</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asclepius" title="Asclepius">Asclepius</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a Thessalian physician who was struck down by Zeus, to be later recovered by his father Apollo</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Attis" title="Attis">Attis</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a consort of Cybele, granted immortality as one of her attendants</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bolina" title="Bolina">Bolina</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a mortal woman transformed into an immortal nymph by Apollo</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Dioscuri" class="mw-redirect" title="Dioscuri">Dioscuri</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), divine twins
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Castor_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Castor (mythology)">Castor</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Castor_and_Pollux" title="Castor and Pollux">Pollux</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>)</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Endymion_(mythology)" title="Endymion (mythology)">Endymion</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), lover of Selene, granted eternal sleep so as never to age or die</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ganymede_(mythology)" title="Ganymede (mythology)">Ganymede</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a handsome Trojan prince, abducted by Zeus and made cup-bearer of the gods</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Glaucus" title="Glaucus">Glaucus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), the fisherman's sea god, made immortal after eating a magical herb</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hemithea_(mythology)" title="Hemithea (mythology)">Hemithea</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>) and Parthenos (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), princesses of the Island of <a href="/wiki/Naxos_(island)" class="mw-redirect" title="Naxos (island)">Naxos</a> who leapt into the sea to escape their father's wrath; Apollo transformed them into demi-goddesses</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Heracles" title="Heracles">Heracles</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), ascended hero</li></ul>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg/220px-Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="213" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg/330px-Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg/440px-Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1905" data-file-height="1845" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Athena pouring a drink for Heracles, who wears the skin of the <a href="/wiki/Nemean_Lion" class="mw-redirect" title="Nemean Lion">Nemean Lion</a></div></div></div>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Ino_(Greek_mythology)" title="Ino (Greek mythology)">Ino</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a Theban princess who became the sea goddess Leucothea</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lampsace" title="Lampsace">Lampsace</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a semi-historical Bebrycian princess honored as goddess for her assistance to the Greeks</li>
<li>The Leucippides (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), wives of the Dioscuri
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Phoebe_(Leucippides)" class="mw-redirect" title="Phoebe (Leucippides)">Phoebe</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), wife of Pollux</li>
<li>Hilaera (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), wife of Castor</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Minos" title="Minos">Minos</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a king of Crete, appointed as a Judge of the Dead in the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orithyia_(Athenian)" class="mw-redirect" title="Orithyia (Athenian)">Orithyia</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), an Athenian princess abducted by Boreas and made the goddess of cold, gusty mountain winds</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Palaemon_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Palaemon (mythology)">Palaemon</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), a Theban prince, made into a sea god along with his mother, Ino</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Philoctetes" title="Philoctetes">Philoctetes</a> (<a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Ancient Greek language">Ancient Greek</a>: <span lang="grc"></span>), was the son of King <a href="/wiki/Poeas" title="Poeas">Poeas</a> of <a href="/wiki/Meliboea" title="Meliboea">Meliboea</a> in <a href="/wiki/Thessaly" title="Thessaly">Thessaly</a>. He was a famous archer, fought at the <a href="/wiki/Trojan_War" title="Trojan War">Trojan War</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phylonoe" class="mw-redirect" title="Phylonoe">Phylonoe</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), daughter of <a href="/wiki/Tyndareus" title="Tyndareus">Tyndareus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Leda_(mythology)" title="Leda (mythology)">Leda</a>, made immortal by Artemis</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Psyche_(mythology)" title="Psyche (mythology)">Psyche</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), goddess of the soul</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Semele" title="Semele">Semele</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), mortal mother of <a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a>, who later was made the goddess Thyone (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tenes" title="Tenes">Tenes</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text"></span>), was a hero of the island of <a href="/wiki/Tenedos" title="Tenedos">Tenedos</a></li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Heroes">Heroes</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Abderus" title="Abderus">Abderus</a>, aided Heracles during his eighth labour and was killed by the <a href="/wiki/Mares_of_Diomedes" title="Mares of Diomedes">Mares of Diomedes</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Achilles" title="Achilles">Achilles</a> ( or ), hero of the <a href="/wiki/Trojan_War" title="Trojan War">Trojan War</a> and a central character in <a href="/wiki/Homer" title="Homer">Homer</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Iliad" title="Iliad">Iliad</a></i></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeneas" title="Aeneas">Aeneas</a> (), a hero of the Trojan War and progenitor of the Roman people</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ajax_the_Great" title="Ajax the Great">Ajax the Great</a> ( ), a hero of the Trojan War and king of <a href="/wiki/Salamis_Island" title="Salamis Island">Salamis</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ajax_the_Lesser" title="Ajax the Lesser">Ajax the Lesser</a> ( ), a hero of the Trojan War and leader of the <a href="/wiki/Locrians" title="Locrians">Locrian</a> army</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphitryon" title="Amphitryon">Amphitryon</a> (), Theban general who rescued Thebes from the <a href="/wiki/Teumessian_fox" title="Teumessian fox">Teumessian fox</a>; his wife was Alcmene, mother of Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antilochus" title="Antilochus">Antilochus</a> (), Son of Nestor sacrificed himself to save his father in the Trojan War along with other deeds of valor</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bellerophon" title="Bellerophon">Bellerophon</a> (), hero who slew the <a href="/wiki/Chimera_(mythology)" title="Chimera (mythology)">Chimera</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bouzyges" title="Bouzyges">Bouzyges</a>, a hero credited with inventing agricultural practices such as yoking oxen to a plough</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Castor_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Castor (mythology)">Castor</a>, the mortal Dioscuri twin; after Castor's death, his immortal brother Pollux shared his divinity with him in order that they might remain together</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chrysippus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Chrysippus (mythology)">Chrysippus</a> (), a divine hero of Elis</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Daedalus" title="Daedalus">Daedalus</a> (), creator of the <a href="/wiki/Labyrinth" title="Labyrinth">labyrinth</a> and great inventor, until King <a href="/wiki/Minos" title="Minos">Minos</a> trapped him in his own creation.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Diomedes" title="Diomedes">Diomedes</a> (), a king of Argos and hero of the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eleusis_(mythology)" title="Eleusis (mythology)">Eleusis</a> ( or ), eponymous hero of the town of <a href="/wiki/Eleusis" title="Eleusis">Eleusis</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eunostus_(hero)" title="Eunostus (hero)">Eunostus</a>, a Boeotian hero</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ganymede_(mythology)" title="Ganymede (mythology)">Ganymede</a> (), Trojan hero and lover of Zeus, who was given immortality and appointed cup-bearer to the gods</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hector" title="Hector">Hector</a> (), hero of the Trojan War and champion of the Trojan people</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Icarus" title="Icarus">Icarus</a> (), the son of the master craftsman <a href="/wiki/Daedalus" title="Daedalus">Daedalus</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iolaus" title="Iolaus">Iolaus</a> (), nephew of <a href="/wiki/Heracles" title="Heracles">Heracles</a> who aided his uncle in one of his Labors</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Jason" title="Jason">Jason</a> (), leader of the Argonauts</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Meleager" title="Meleager">Meleager</a> (), a hero who sailed with the Argonauts and killed the Calydonian Boar</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Odysseus" title="Odysseus">Odysseus</a> ( or ), a hero and king of Ithaca whose adventures are the subject of Homer's <i><a href="/wiki/Odyssey" title="Odyssey">Odyssey</a></i>; he also played a key role during the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orpheus" title="Orpheus">Orpheus</a> (), a legendary musician and poet who attempted to retrieve his dead wife from the Underworld</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pandion_(hero)" title="Pandion (hero)">Pandion</a> (), the eponymous hero of the <a href="/wiki/Phyle" title="Phyle">Attic tribe</a> Pandionis, usually assumed to be one of the legendary Athenian kings <a href="/wiki/Pandion_I" title="Pandion I">Pandion I</a> or <a href="/wiki/Pandion_II" title="Pandion II">Pandion II</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Perseus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Perseus (mythology)">Perseus</a> (), son of Zeus and the founder-king of Mycenae and slayer of the Gorgon Medusa</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Theseus" title="Theseus">Theseus</a> (), son of Poseidon and a king of Athens and slayer of the <a href="/wiki/Minotaur" title="Minotaur">Minotaur</a></li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Notable_women">Notable women</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Alcestis" title="Alcestis">Alcestis</a> (), daughter of Pelias and wife of Admetus, who was known for her devotion to her husband</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amymone" title="Amymone">Amymone</a>, the one daughter of Danaus who refused to murder her husband, thus escaping her sisters' punishment</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Andromache" title="Andromache">Andromache</a> (), wife of Hector</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Andromeda_(mythology)" title="Andromeda (mythology)">Andromeda</a> (), wife of Perseus, who was placed among the constellations after her death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antigone" title="Antigone">Antigone</a> (), daughter of Oedipus and Jocasta</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arachne" title="Arachne">Arachne</a> (), a skilled weaver, transformed by Athena into a spider for her blasphemy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ariadne" title="Ariadne">Ariadne</a> (), daughter of Minos, king of Crete, who aided Theseus in overcoming the Minotaur and became the wife of Dionysus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Atalanta" title="Atalanta">Atalanta</a> (), fleet-footed heroine who participated in the Calydonian Boar hunt and the quest for the <a href="/wiki/Golden_Fleece" title="Golden Fleece">Golden Fleece</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Briseis" title="Briseis">Briseis</a>, a princess of <a href="/wiki/Lyrnessus" title="Lyrnessus">Lyrnessus</a>, taken by Achilles as a war prize</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Caeneus" title="Caeneus">Caeneus</a>, formerly Caenis, a woman who was transformed into a man and became a mighty warrior</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cassandra" title="Cassandra">Cassandra</a>, a princess of Troy cursed to see the future but never to be believed</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cassiopeia_(Queen_of_Aethiopia)" class="mw-redirect" title="Cassiopeia (Queen of Aethiopia)">Cassiopeia</a> (), queen of <a href="/wiki/Ethiopia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ethiopia (mythology)">thiopia</a> and mother of <a href="/wiki/Andromeda_(mythology)" title="Andromeda (mythology)">Andromeda</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Clytemnestra" title="Clytemnestra">Clytemnestra</a>, sister of Helen and unfaithful wife of Agamemnon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dana%C3%AB" title="Dana">Dana</a>, the mother of Perseus by Zeus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Deianeira" class="mw-redirect" title="Deianeira">Deianeira</a>, the third wife and unwitting killer of Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Electra" title="Electra">Electra</a>, daughter of Agamemnon and Clytemnestra, she aided her brother Orestes in plotting revenge against their mother for the murder of their father</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Europa_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Europa (mythology)">Europa</a>, a Phoenician woman, abducted by Zeus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hecuba" title="Hecuba">Hecuba</a> (), wife of Priam, king of Troy, and mother of nineteen of his children</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Helen_of_Troy" title="Helen of Troy">Helen</a>, daughter of Zeus and Leda, whose abduction brought about the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hermione_(mythology)" title="Hermione (mythology)">Hermione</a> (), daughter of Menelaus and Helen; wife of Neoptolemus, and later Orestes</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iphigenia" title="Iphigenia">Iphigenia</a>, daughter of Agamemnon and Clytemnestra; Agamemnon sacrificed her to Artemis in order to appease the goddess</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ismene" title="Ismene">Ismene</a>, sister of Antigone</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Jocasta" title="Jocasta">Jocasta</a>, mother and wife of Oedipus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Medea" title="Medea">Medea</a>, a sorceress and wife of Jason, who killed her own children to punish Jason for his infidelity</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Medusa" title="Medusa">Medusa</a>, a mortal woman transformed into a hideous gorgon by Athena</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Niobe" title="Niobe">Niobe</a>, a daughter of Tantalus who declared herself to be superior to Leto, causing Artemis and Apollo to kill her fourteen children</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pandora" title="Pandora">Pandora</a>, the first woman</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Penelope" title="Penelope">Penelope</a>, loyal wife of Odysseus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phaedra_(mythology)" title="Phaedra (mythology)">Phaedra</a>, daughter of Minos and wife of Theseus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Polyxena" title="Polyxena">Polyxena</a>, the youngest daughter of Priam, sacrificed to the ghost of Achilles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Semele" title="Semele">Semele</a>, mortal mother of Dionysus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thrace_(mythology)" title="Thrace (mythology)">Thrace</a>, the daughter of Oceanus and Parthenope, and sister of Europa</li></ul>
</div>
